      <title>Accidental line-wrapping in Base64</title>
      
      <link>https://zerokspot.com/weblog/2025/07/03/accidental-line-wraps-in-base64/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 03 Jul 2025 14:58:08 +0200</pubDate>
      
      <guid>/weblog/2025/07/03/accidental-line-wraps-in-base64/</guid>
      <description>
          &lt;p&gt;This is one of those findings that are just stupid. There was a bug in some CI script where we just manually generate the Basic-Auth HTTP header using something in a secret and the &lt;code&gt;base64&lt;/code&gt; utility:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;auth_header=$(echo -n ‚Äú$USER_ID:$TOKEN‚Äù | base64)
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;p&gt;That doesn‚Äôt look completely wrong, does it? Turns out, base64 on Linux has a different behavior compared to, let‚Äôs say, MacOS: It will by default use line-wrapping at 76 characters:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;USER_ID=hello_world
TOKEN=01234567890123456789012345678901234567890123456789012345678901234567890123456789
auth_header=$(echo -n ‚Äú$USER_ID:$TOKEN‚Äù | base64)
echo $auth_header
aGVsbG9fd29ybGQ6MDEyMzQ1Njc4OTAxMjM0NTY3ODkwMTIzNDU2Nzg5MDEyMzQ1Njc4OTAxMjM0
NTY3ODkwMTIzNDU2Nzg5MDEyMzQ1Njc4OTAxMjM0NTY3ODk=
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;p&gt;Yes, there‚Äôs a newline here when using that 80 character token. If you had run that script on MacOS, no such line-break would be part of the output.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Especially for scripting my assumption is that most of the time you actually do not want line-breaks in your Base64 output. So if you‚Äôre on Linux, always make sure to use &lt;code&gt;base64 -w 0&lt;/code&gt; unless you want that wrapping.&lt;/p&gt;

      </description>
    </item>
    
